Things I’ve worn in Mexico. In Womens Group the other night, the topic we explored was ‘Death’. @shivani74 invited a death doula to speak to us, and she shared Atisha’s 9 contemplations on death. One of the contemplations was that we cannot bring our material possessions with us. I thought about all the clothes that I’ve collected and loved on through years and trips and time spent foraging deep online, and what will happen to them when I go. The painstaking process of curating a personal style. 

What’s the point of it all? Is it enough to value self expression and beauty for the sake of it during my brief time on this earth because that’s what it means to be alive and human? I thought about that quote from ep 3 of the Last of Us: “Paying attention to things is how we show love.” I don’t have an answer yet but I’m really starting to love the way I’ve been clothing my little earthly being, even if I can’t take it with me.

The other day @tessaforrest texted me out of the blue to ask if my Saturn was in Pisces, because Saturn just entered Pisces on March 7, which technically meant that I was entering my Saturn’s Return. Thats when Saturn “returns” to its position when you were born, and it represents a shift into the next stage of your life / major existential crises / a time of coming into alignment - it usually happens 27-31 for most people.

I’m not a huge astrology girly, but it makes sense - your late 20’s as a time of rapid change and growth, a period of re-evaluation, facing your trauma properly, quitting your job, leaving your relationship. That all happened for me in the last three years, in a really big, intense, expansive way. It felt pretty tough, so much growth at such a rapid clip that it completely exhausted me. I assumed I had finished my Saturn’s Return. When I realized it actually only just began, I freaked out at the idea of another 3 years of non-stop existential growth and work.

A few months ago, I stopped taking on as much work as Scallion Pancake, in order to give myself time and space to return to the creative practices (photography, writing) I was deeply engaged with when I was 14, and which I let myself de-prioritize as an adult because it never occurred to me that I was good enough or worthy enough to. There’s so much that comes with that transition — learning how to encourage myself in the absence of having anyone do that for me as a kid, of getting over the fact that I’m trying to make art at the age of 30, the value of being solitary, of measuring fulfillment in a way that feels totally alien from a lifetime spent in pursuit of traditional capitalist success (going fast, being busy, doing it all). 

Whether or not I wholly believe astrology, I’m glad for the gentle reminder that you don’t stop growing just because you don’t want to. I’m still changing - a lot, but maybe growth doesn’t always have to be so difficult if you release your control over it, if you accept it as a simple rule of being alive. Godspeed and good luck to all who just entered their Saturn’s Return in Pisces. 💖

These are from the first year I took film photos at age 15 with my family’s old hand me down Minolta 7000AF (which I still own). 

I don’t have any of these negatives - I really never knew that photography could be viable as a job for someone like me, and never thought to keep them. These are originally scans of printed photos I developed at Big W (an Australian discount target type joint) during family outings to the mall. 

As I was grabbing these off my old Facebook albums, I felt so grateful for little Jess for carrying that brick of a camera everywhere and relentlessly documenting everything and everyone around her. Every time I look at these photos I think about how real they feel, how much they completely capture my high school friends in their most candid and vulnerable versions of self, before we really knew or had a reason to filter or obfuscate. Who we were able to be in the each other’s company.

Me n my psoriasis 🤝 Florida sun.

It hit 75+ in NY the other day. I’m mid flare up right now, and it’s particularly bad on my thighs and calves. I wanted to tan and read in a skimpy bikini in the park because that’s one of my favorite things to do as a sun starved BK girl, and it felt sad to let something like my skin get in the way of that. Walking outside for the first time in months in shorts took recruiting all my energy to acknowledge and let go of the steady stream of, “people are looking” “it looks gross” etc etc. When I took my clothes off at the park, I couldn’t help but notice how carefree everyone looked to be in their smooth skin, and I envied them. 

I kept looking at the red flaky spots on my legs, obsessing, before noticing how nice the sun felt on my skin—and that my entire experience was being taken from me because I was so so fixated on something so utterly insignificant. I was fixated on vanity instead of the real breeze on my skin, instead of the green on the trees and the warmth in the air. Idk if being a woman means forever dealing with the repercussions of being socialized in an environment that encourages a hyper fixation on how you look, but I’m realizing if it’s not my body or my skin or my hair, it’s always going to be something else, and that’s robbing me of being totally in the present moment, and how sad is that! I think I get better at it every time I catch myself and make that switch, and ima be doing that in the sun in my tiny bikinis all week in florida :) #psoriasis

The gradual transition to 30 has been hand in hand with a twisty contemplation on how I want to dress, how I accumulate things, how I represent and express the person I am as these shifts are happening inside of me. My body is changing, my style is changing, my brain feels like it’s changing too. It’s a weird feeling to actually notice the aging — not just the physicality of it, but also the churning and release in my spirit and my mind that I can actually perceptibly notice for the first time (do you remember turning from a teen to an adult? I don’t). 

All that’s to say I’m letting go of a lot of clothes I’ve been holding onto this Saturday at @roguegarms with @elenataber. Things I kept around me for my whole 20s believing an occasion would come up (who needs 15 ball gowns?) but which are now giving way to this urge to let go and to create space for the person I’ll be in this new decade of life. There’ll be some special vintage things I got in Europe in my early 20s, trendy pieces I don’t wear anymore, some brands. Come scoop them and give them the adventures I never did. 11.30-7pm, 53 Stanton Street. Saturday 4/29.

God is nature / some of the greatest three days of my life hiking through the Dolomites hut to hut 😭

As I’ve been walking and walking and walking over the last week in the indescribable surreal hallucination that is the Dolomites, I’ve been thinking a lot about privilege and the I-get-to of all of this. Of having a body that can move me through miles uphill, of all my senses intact, of being able to drive and have resource and time to go to see something like this. To have a deep friendship with @jillarielle, someone I love and get along with enough to spend a week sleeping in the same beds (and to split costs, making this trip affordable). Of being alive at the right time to see the mind boggling expressions of Mother Nature in far flung places- what would this look like if I was born in 5 generations time? Every trip I take ends up being the best trip I’ve ever been on. Everything I see is more unbelievable. How lucky that life can keep getting sweeter and more surprising?

The one time I looked cute n pretty in Italy in between being caked with mud and sweat. Going to miss the tramezzini (lil italian white bread crust less sandwiches), the aperol with white wine, and the way the altitude checks my ego on my cardio capacity. Most of all I’ll miss the mountains that wait around every corner, but I have 7 rolls of film travelling with me to Biarritz to be developed so I can relive it all over again. 💗🦋

Blogs were the way I first found my way on the internet. In between coding websites for blogskins.com, posting my insane thrift store lewks on lookbook.nu, lurking on Livejournal and running a silly inspiration account on Tumblr, writing and shooting for my own blog was a constant throughout it. 

I designed and coded my own layouts for Jess Loves Fred, my OG blog (Fred was the name of my Canon EOS 400D, one of the first cameras I owned). When I read my old journals or these old blog posts, and the way I used to describe myself, it surprises me how much remains the same. I thought that maybe I’d become this completely different person as an adult, and in many ways I am, but in more ways I remain the same girl geeked out on writing and photography, with lots and lots of feelings. 

I just wanted to have a place to share writing and photos again without the pressure of building a brand or maximizing engagement or angering the algorithmic gods yada yada yada. It’s a room of my own, and I’d love to hang with you there. You’ll find my photo portfolio and writings on anything + everything, updated whenever I feel like it.

S/O to @derekbenedict for helping me bring this thing to life, and my bb @tessaforrest for the name word mark. :) Best viewed on Desktop > www.jesstran.me <3 and if you can remember this era of my life, thanks for riding with me for so long.

Self portrait on film in Venice

Traunsee Lake / Gmunden, Austria. 

I went to Vienna to visit @dein_lenz and @dreamcastar. It was the last leg of my month in Europe. When I got there, they suggested we go straight to the lake, a 2 hour drive from Vienna. I had no idea we were going (and had never even heard of Gmunden before that), and afterwards when it was time to go home I went straight to the airport from the lake. 

We spent the days eating excellent Laurenz fried eggs, swimming furiously away when the seaweed would tickle my feet, hosting little workshops to teach each other Ableton/drawing/social media/networking, watching the Netflix doc Merpeople and taking the boat out to swim off the side of a cliff. I realized I had never swum in a lake before. I remember the water felt cold and clear and heavy without saline. I even jumped off the deck and felt really proud of myself even though it took me forever to work up the courage, even though the way I landed forced so much water up my butt.

Hawaii / Sydney dump. Jetstar flights were $350 return between Sydney <> Honolulu so I made my biennial return to the land of plentiful sunshine and banh uot with Cody in tow. Leaving my family feels harder the older I get, knowing that the two year leaps mean my parents will have shrunk even more, that my friends will suddenly have moved countries or had babies, that I will feel like a completely different person. Going home and leaving again is always an emotional affair for me. I’ll probably write more about it  when I’m up from jet lag in the middle of the night and think about how I already miss my family and a place I couldn’t wait to leave and now ache to go back to. The first photo was taken in our hotel the morning we left Australia lol 😭
